But in the modern world there are many independent sovereignties, and the Law oi Nations covers questions at issue between the citizens ol these different States. To this purpose the civil law, in view oi the circum· stances in which it grew up, is not adopted. The civil law, commentators on it and precedente from antiquity are frequently cited, but rather by way ol confirming or illustrating rules de· rived from contemporary usage. At the same time Gentili stands between the ancient and the modern world, and his inheritance from the ancient world is evident in many ways. It comes out in the scholastic torm oi his argumentation, which carries us back to the schools oi the Middle Ages. It appears occa· sionally in a casuistical argument, as it does in the fanciful distinction which he tries to make in one passage ²⁹ between the meanings ol certain words, or in the insistence in another connection on an exact analogy between physical and legal processes.²⁰ ,

Great as were his aehievements in the field oi international law, yet in stemming the tide in England which was setting to· ward the common law he was doomed to failure. He fought earnestly in this cause, but it was a lost cause, as be himself seems to recognize at the close oi one oi his speeches recorded in the Advocatio:

Granted that these pettiioggers oi the common law have pushed their way into marriage cases, into testamentary, ecclesiastieal and maritime cases, and into others oi this sort, which still have always been held to be the peculiar province oi those versed in the civil law, but granted that they have pushed their way in, simply because those cases had to do with Englishmen, with English concerns, with transactions carried on in England; on this account, pray, shall they rush in and seiae these cases involving foreigners? Even though this state oi affairs is in part to be explained by the daily increasing power oi those who study the common law, still the old landmarks should be preserved.²¹

In one of the two tasks then to which he devoted himself, he in part failed, I mean in maintaining the supremacy ol the civil law over the common law in regulating those transactions in which the civil law seemed to him especially applicable.
